'''Noah Junior Sadiki''' (born 17 December 2004) is a  professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a central midfielder for [[Premier League]] club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. Born in Belgium, he plays for the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]].

==Club career==

===Anderlecht===
Born in Brussels, Sadiki first joined [[R.S.C. Anderlecht]] at the age of six at under-7 level and progressed through all of the junior teams up to under-21 level.<ref name="contract">{{cite web|url=https://www.rsca.be/en/sadiki|title=NOAH SADIKI SIGNS HIS FIRST PROFESSIONAL CONTRACT|publisher=soccerway.com|date=10 February 2022|accessdate=3 July 2023}}</ref> He impressed for Robin Veldman's under-21 team and caught the eye of first team manager [[Vincent Kompany]] who played him in two friendly matches in October 2021 and January 2022.<ref name="contract"/> He signed his first professional contract in February 2022 on a one-year deal, with the option of a further year.<ref name="contract"/>

===Union SG===
On 27 July 2023, Sadiki left Anderlecht and joined [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Union SG]] on a four-year contract, for a reported fee of €1.4 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 July 2023 |title=Noah Sadiki is leaving RSC Anderlecht and joins RUSG {{!}} RSC Anderlecht |url=https://www.rsca.be/en/noahsadiki |access-date=27 July 2023 |website=www.rsca.be |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=27 July 2023 |title=Sadiki rejoint l'Union pour 1,4 million d'euros |trans-title=Sadiki joins Union for 1.4 million euros |url=https://www.dhnet.be/sports/football/division-1a/union-saint-gilloise/2023/07/27/sadiki-rejoint-lunion-pour-14-million-deuros-RH7FR6V2CRB5NE5ZYKDGCDDFH4/ |access-date=27 July 2023 |website=DHnet |language=fr}}</ref>

===Sunderland===
On 4 July 2025, Sadiki left Union SG and joined [[Premier League]] club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on a five year contract, for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=4 July 2025 |title= Sadiki signs five-year deal at Sunderland |url= https://www.safc.com/news/2025/july/04/sadiki-signs-five-year-deal-at-sunderland/|access-date=4 July 2025|website=www.safc.com|language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in Belgium, Sadiki is of DR Congolese descent. Sadiki also holds both Congolese and Belgium citizenship from his parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foot-africa.com/fr/afrique/rd-congo/can-2024-binationaux-rdc/|title=CAN 2024 : 4 Binationaux Dans Le Collimateur De La RDC|date=October 2, 2023|language=French}}</ref> He is a youth international for Belgium having played up to the [[Belgium national under-20 football team|Belgium U20]]s, but opted to play for the DR Congo in September 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walfoot.be/news/2023-09-07/la-belgique-perd-un-talent--ce-joueur-de-lunion-a-opte-pour-une-autre-selection|title=La Belgique perd un talent : ce joueur de l'Union a opté pour une autre sélection !|date=September 7, 2023|website=Walfoot.be|language=French}}</ref> In September 2023 he was called up to play for the DR Congo U21s to play in their friendly matches against SK Lommel and Sparta Rotterdam. He played his first minutes in a 3–2 loss to Sparta Rotterdam.<ref>{{cite web |title=La République Démocratique du Congo ou la Belgique ? Sadiki a fait son choix |url=https://www.footnews.be/news/387487/la-republique-democratique-du-congo-ou-la-belgique-sadiki-a-fait-son-choix |website=footnews.be |access-date=7 September 2024 |language=French |date=11 September 2023 }}</ref> In October 2023, Sadiki was called up to the [[DR Congo national under-20 football team|DR Congo U21]]s to play in a two match series against [[Tunisia national under-20 football team|Tunisia U21]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fecofa.cd/article/u21-la-rdc-en-double-confrontation-contre-la-tunisie-a-tunis|title=U21: La RDC en double confrontation contre la Tunisie a tunis|website=www.fecofa.cd|language=French}}</ref>

Sadiki made his debut for the senior [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]] on 6 September 2024 in a [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group H|Africa Cup of Nations qualifier]] against Guinea at the [[Stade des Martyrs]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ESPN|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/715407/guinea-congo-dr|title=DR Congo v Guinea game report|date=6 September 2024}}</ref>

